      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="MM3-intro">mūṉṟāvatu malarvaṉampukkapāṭṭu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">The third song, in which [Maṇimēkalai and Cutamati] enter the flower grove.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p type="edition" />
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">
        </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="MM3">
          <l> vayanta mālaikku mātavi yuraitta</l>
          <l>vuyaṅkunōy varuttat turaimuṉ ṟōṉṟi</l>
          <l>māmalar nāṟṟam pōṉmaṇi mēkalaik</l>
          <l>kētu nikaḻcci yetirntuḷa tātaliṟ</l>
          <l>ṟantaiyun tāyun tānaṉi yuḻanta</l>
          <l>ventuya riṭumpai ceviyakam vetuppak</l>
          <l>kāta ṉeñcaṅ kalaṅkik kārikai</l>
          <l>mātar ceṅkaṇ varivaṉap paḻittup</l>
          <l>pulampunī ruruṭṭip potiyaviḻ naṟumala</l>
          <l>rilaṅkitaḻ mālaiyai yiṭṭunī rāṭṭa</l>
          <l> mātavi maṇimē kalaimuka nōkkit</l>
          <l>tāmarai taṇmati cērntatu pōlak</l>
          <l>kāmar ceṅkaiyiṟ kaṇṇīr māṟṟit</l>
          <l>tūnīr mālai tūttakai yiḻantatu</l>
          <l>nikarmalar nīyē koṇarvā yeṉṟalu</l>
          <l> matumalark kuḻaliyoṭu māmalar toṭukkuñ</l>
          <l>cutamati kēṭṭut tuyaroṭuṅ kūṟuṅ</l>
          <l>kuravark kuṟṟa koṭuntuyar kēṭṭut</l>
          <l>taṇiyāt tuṉpan talaittalai yeytu</l>
          <l>maṇimē kalaitaṉ matimukan taṉṉu</l>
          <l>ḷaṇitikaḻ nīlat tāymala roṭṭiya</l>
          <l>kaṭaimaṇi yukunīr kaṇṭaṉa ṉāyiṟ</l>
          <l>paṭaiyiṭṭu naṭuṅkuṅ kāmaṉ pāvaiyai</l>
          <l>yāṭavar kaṇṭā lakaṟalu muṇṭō</l>
          <l>pēṭiya raṉṟō peṟṟiyi ṉiṉṟiṭi</l>
          <l> ṉāṅkaṉa maṉṟiyu maṇiyiḻai kēḷā</l>
          <l>yīṅkin nakarat tiyāṉvaruṅ kāraṇam</l>
          <l>pārā vāram palvaḷam paḻuṉiya</l>
          <l>kārāḷar caṇpaiyiṟ kaucika ṉeṉpō</l>
          <l>ṉirupiṟap pāḷa ṉorumaka ḷuḷḷē</l>
          <l>ṉorutaṉi yañcē ṉōrā neñcamō</l>
          <l>ṭārā mattiṭai yalarkoy vēṉṟaṉai</l>
          <l>māruta vēkaṉeṉ pāṉōr viñcaiyaṉ</l>
          <l>ṟiruviḻai mūtūr tēvarkōṟ keṭutta</l>
          <l>peruviḻāk kāṇum peṟṟiyiṉ varuvōṉ</l>
          <l>ṟāraṉ mālaiyaṉ ṟamaṉiyap pūṇiṉaṉ</l>
          <l>pārōr kāṇāp palartoḻu paṭimaiya</l>
          <l>ṉeṭuttaṉa ṉeṟkoṇ ṭeḻuntaṉaṉ vicumpiṟ</l>
          <l>paṭuttaṉa ṉāṅkavaṉ pāṉmaiyē ṉāyiṉē</l>
          <l>ṉāṅkava ṉīṅkeṉai yakaṉṟukaṇ māṟi</l>
          <l>nīṅkiṉaṉ ṟaṉpati neṭṭiṭai yāyiṉu</l>
          <l>maṇippūṅ kompar maṇimē kalaitāṉ</l>
          <l>ṟaṉittalar koyyun takaimaiya ḷallaḷ</l>

        </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l corresp="2ab"> The debilitating pain </l>
          <l corresp="1"> with which Matavi had spoken to Vayantamālai</l>
          <l corresp="2cd"> became apparent [to Maṇimēkalai] during [Mātavi's] speech about [her]
            grief.</l>
          <l corresp="4"> The reality of Cause and Effect confronted </l>
          <l corresp="3">Maṇimēkalai like the scent of huge flowers. </l>
          <l corresp="6">Pain burnt the inside of her ears with the [same] hot, miserable agony </l>
          <l corresp="5"> in which [her] father and mother had suffered so much. </l>
          <l corresp="7">Love was stirred up in the girl's heart,</l>
          <l corresp="8">destroying [her] beauty with streaks in [her] beautiful, red eyes. </l>
          <l corresp="9ab">Sending tears of sorrow rolling down [her cheeks], </l>
          <l corresp="10abc">[love] poured tears onto [her] garland of shining petals </l>
          <l corresp="9cd">and fragrant blossoms opening their buds</l>
          <l corresp="10d"> and bathed [the garland in tears]. </l>

          <l corresp="11">Mātavi, looking into Maṇimēkalai's face,</l>

          <l corresp="13">and wiping away [her] tears with [her] lovely red hand,</l>

          <l corresp="12">like a lotus joining the cool moon,</l>

          <l corresp="14">said, 'The garland of pure nature has lots its pure fitness.</l>

          <l corresp="15">[Go and] fetch shining blossoms [to make a new garland]!'</l>


          <l corresp="17a"> Cutamati, </l>
          <l corresp="16"> who was weaving big flowers [into a garland] with the girl whose hair was
            coiled with nectar-[filled] blossoms (Maṇimēkalai),</l>
          <l corresp="17bcd"> [over-]heard [what Mātavi said to Maṇimēkalai] and began to speak
            sorrowfully: </l>
          <l corresp="22-23c"> 'If Kāmadeva sees the tears shed from the rims of the sapphire[-like]
            eyes </l>
          <l corresp="20"> upon Maṇimēkalai's moon-like face— </l>
          <l corresp="21"> to rival the choice blossoms on an ornamental gliterring blue lotus— </l>
          <l corresp="19"> as she suffers unappeasable grief over and over again,</l>
          <l corresp="18"> listenting to the great misfortune suffered by [her] respected parents,</l>
          <l corresp="23ab"> he will lay down [his] bow and tremble. </l>
          <l corresp="23d-24"> And if men see the maiden, will they [ever] leave [her alone]? </l>
          <l corresp="25"> Would they not [have to] be hermaphrodites, if—because of [their]
            character—they remained unmoved? </l>
          <l corresp="26"> Moreover, listen, O [lady of] choice jewels,</l>
          <l corresp="27"> to the reason why I came to this city here.</l>
          <l corresp="30"> I am the only daughter of a twice-born </l>
          <l corresp="29"> called Kaucikaṉ from [the town of] Caṇpai, [which belongs to] the Vēḷāḷa-s, </l>
          <l corresp="28"> where much wealth of the sea ripens.</l>
          <l corresp="31"> Not being afraid all on my own, with reckless heart, </l>
          <l corresp="32"> I was plucking blossoms in the pleasure-garden, </l>
          <l corresp="33"> when a Vidyādhara called Mārutavēkaṉ, </l>
          <l corresp="35"> who had come to see the great festival </l>
          <l corresp="34"> put on for the king of the gods in the ancient town beloved of Śrī
            (Kāvirippūmpaṭṭiṉam),</l>
          <l corresp="36"> wearing a flower garland, a jewel necklace and golden ornaments, </l>
          <l corresp="37"> having a form worshipped by many, not seen by mortals, </l>
          <l corresp="38"> picked me up, rose into the sky, taking me [with him],</l>
          <l corresp="39"> and left me there. I became his property. </l>
          <l corresp="40-41"> [Then] he, leaving me here, was gone was gone from there in the blink of an eye,
            although it is a long way to/ from his place. </l>
          <l corresp="42"> [Therefore] Maṇimēkalai herself, [who is] like a sapphire-[coloured] flowering branch, </l>
          <l corresp="43"> is not one who is fit to pluck blossoms on her own. </l>


        </lg>
      </div>
